# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: sequential-diverging-palettes
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:sequential-diverging-palettes/choropleth-map] Choropleth maps provide an easy way to visualize how a variable varies across a geographic area or show the level of variability within a region.
[src:sequential-diverging-palettes/choropleth-map] A heat map or isarithmic map is similar but uses regions drawn according to the pattern of the variable, rather than the *a priori* geographic areas of choropleth maps.
[src:sequential-diverging-palettes/choropleth-map] The earliest known choropleth map was created in 1826 by Baron Pierre Charles Dupin, depicting the availability of basic education in France by department.
[src:sequential-diverging-palettes/choropleth-map] More "*cartes teintées*" ("tinted maps") were soon produced in France to visualize other "moral statistics" on education, disease, crime, and living conditions.
[src:sequential-diverging-palettes/choropleth-map] Choropleth maps quickly gained popularity in several countries due to the increasing availability of demographic data compiled from national Censuses, starting with a series of choropleth maps published in the official reports of the 1841 Census of Ireland.
[src:sequential-diverging-palettes/choropleth-map] When Chromolithography became widely available after 1850, color was increasingly added to choropleth maps.
[src:sequential-diverging-palettes/choropleth-map] The term "choropleth map" was introduced in 1938 by the geographer John Kirtland Wright, and was in common usage among cartographers by the 1940s.
[src:sequential-diverging-palettes/choropleth-map] Also in 1938, Glenn Trewartha reintroduced them as "ratio maps", but this term did not survive.
[src:sequential-diverging-palettes/choropleth-map] A choropleth map brings together two datasets: spatial data representing a partition of geographic space into distinct *districts*, and *statistical data* representing a variable aggregated within each district.
[src:sequential-diverging-palettes/choropleth-map] There are two common conceptual models of how these interact in a choropleth map: in one view, which may be called "district dominant", the districts (often existing governmental units) are the focus, in which a variety of attributes are collected, including the variable being mapped.
[src:sequential-diverging-palettes/choropleth-map] In the other view, which may be called "variable dominant", the focus is on the variable as a geographic phenomenon (say, the Latino population), with a real-world distribution, and the partitioning of it into districts is merely a convenient measurement technique.
[src:sequential-diverging-palettes/choropleth-map] That is, boundaries of the colored districts may or may not coincide with the location of changes in the geographic distribution being studied.
[src:sequential-diverging-palettes/choropleth-map] This is in direct contrast to chorochromatic and isarithmic maps, in which region boundaries are defined by patterns in the geographic distribution of the subject phenomenon.
[src:sequential-diverging-palettes/choropleth-map] A prime example of this would be elections, in which the vote total for each district determines its elected representative.
[src:sequential-diverging-palettes/choropleth-map] However, it can result in a number of issues, generally due to the fact that the constant color applied to each aggregation district makes it look homogeneous, masking an unknown degree of variation of the variable within the district.
[src:sequential-diverging-palettes/choropleth-map] For example, a city may include neighborhoods of low, moderate, and high family income, but be colored with one constant "moderate" color.
[src:sequential-diverging-palettes/choropleth-map] Thus, real-world spatial patterns may not conform to the regional unit symbolized.
[src:sequential-diverging-palettes/choropleth-map] Because of this, issues such as the ecological fallacy and the modifiable areal unit problem (MAUP) can lead to major misinterpretations of the data depicted, and other techniques are preferable if one can obtain the necessary data.
[src:sequential-diverging-palettes/choropleth-map] These issues can be somewhat mitigated by using smaller districts, because they show finer variations in the mapped variable, and their smaller visual size and increased number reduces the likelihood that the map user makes judgments about the variation within a single district.
[src:sequential-diverging-palettes/choropleth-map] However, they can make the map overly complex, especially if there is not a meaningful geographic pattern in the variable (i.e., the map looks like randomly scattered colors).
[src:sequential-diverging-palettes/choropleth-map] Although representing specific data in large regions can be misleading, the familiar district shapes can make the map clearer and easier to interpret and remember.
[src:sequential-diverging-palettes/choropleth-map] The choice of regions will ultimately depend on the map's intended audience and purpose.
[src:sequential-diverging-palettes/choropleth-map] Alternatively, the dasymetric technique can sometimes be employed to refine the region boundaries to more closely match actual changes in the subject phenomenon.
[src:sequential-diverging-palettes/choropleth-map] Because of these issues, for many variables, one may prefer an isarithmic (for a quantitative variable) or chorochromatic map (for a qualitative variable), in which the region boundaries are based on the data itself.
[src:sequential-diverging-palettes/choropleth-map] However, in many cases such detailed information is simply not available, and the choropleth map is the only feasible option.
[src:sequential-diverging-palettes/choropleth-map] The variable can also be in any of Stevens' levels of measurement: nominal, ordinal, interval, or ratio, although quantitative (interval/ratio) variables are more commonly used in choropleth maps than qualitative (nominal/ordinal) variables.
[src:sequential-diverging-palettes/choropleth-map] The level of measurement of the individual datum may be different than the aggregate summary statistic.
[src:sequential-diverging-palettes/choropleth-map] For example, a census may ask each individual for his or her "primary spoken language" (nominal), but this may be summarized over all of the individuals in a county as "percent primarily speaking Spanish" (ratio) or as "predominant primary language" (nominal).
[src:sequential-diverging-palettes/choropleth-map] Normalization is the technique of deriving a spatially intensive variable from one or more spatially extensive variables, so that it can be appropriately used in a choropleth map.
[src:sequential-diverging-palettes/choropleth-map] It is similar, but not identical, to the technique of normalization or standardization in statistics.
[src:sequential-diverging-palettes/choropleth-map] Typically, it is accomplished by computing the ratio between two spatially extensive variables.
[src:sequential-diverging-palettes/choropleth-map] These are not equivalent, nor is one better than another.
[src:sequential-diverging-palettes/choropleth-map] Rather, they tell different aspects of a geographic narrative.
[src:sequential-diverging-palettes/choropleth-map] For example, a choropleth map of the population density of the Latino population in Texas visualizes a narrative about the spatial clustering and distribution of that group, while a map of the percent Latino visualizes a narrative of composition and predominance.
[src:sequential-diverging-palettes/choropleth-map] Failure to employ proper normalization will lead to an inappropriate and potentially misleading map in almost all cases.
[src:sequential-diverging-palettes/choropleth-map] This is one of the most common mistakes in cartography, with one study finding that at one point, more than half of United States COVID-19 dashboards hosted by state governments were not employing normalization to their choropleth maps.
[src:sequential-diverging-palettes/choropleth-map] This is one of many issues that contributed to the infodemic surrounding the COVID-19 pandemic, and "might also be a subtle facilitator of the extreme political polarization surrounding measures to combat COVID that has occurred in the United States".
[src:sequential-diverging-palettes/choropleth-map] Every choropleth map has a strategy for mapping values to colors.
[src:sequential-diverging-palettes/choropleth-map] A *classified* choropleth map separates the range of values into classes, with all of the districts in each class being assigned the same color.
[src:sequential-diverging-palettes/choropleth-map] An *unclassed* map (sometimes called *n-class*) directly assigns a color proportional to the value of each district.
[src:sequential-diverging-palettes/choropleth-map] Starting with Dupin's 1826 map, classified choropleth maps have been far more common.
[src:sequential-diverging-palettes/choropleth-map] It is likely that this was originally due to the greater simplicity of applying a limited set of tints; only in the age of computerized cartography have unclassed choropleth maps even been feasible, and until recently, they were still not easy to create in most mapping software.
[src:sequential-diverging-palettes/choropleth-map] Tobler, in formally introducing the unclassed scheme in 1973, asserted that it was a more accurate depiction of the original data, and stated that the primary argument in favor of classification, that it is more readable, needed to be tested.
[src:sequential-diverging-palettes/choropleth-map] Thus, they are able to better see the general patterns in the geographic phenomenon, but not the specific values.
[src:sequential-diverging-palettes/choropleth-map] The primary argument in favor of classed choropleth maps is that it is easier for readers to process, due to the fewer number of distinct shades to recognize, which reduces cognitive load and allows them to precisely match the colors in the map to the values listed in the legend.
[src:sequential-diverging-palettes/choropleth-map] Classification is performed by establishing a *classification rule*, a series of thresholds that partitions the quantitative range of variable values into a series of ordered classes.
[src:sequential-diverging-palettes/choropleth-map] For example, if a dataset of annual Median income by U.S. county includes values between US$20,000 and $150,000, it could be broken into three classes at thresholds of $45,000 and $83,000.
[src:sequential-diverging-palettes/choropleth-map] To avoid confusion, any classification rule should be mutually exclusive and collectively exhaustive, meaning that any possible value falls into exactly one class.
[src:sequential-diverging-palettes/choropleth-map] For example, if a rule establishes a threshold at the value 6.5, it needs to be clear about whether a district with a value of exactly 6.5 will be classified into the lower or upper class (i.e., whether the definition of the lower class is <6.5 or ≤6.5 and whether the upper class is >6.5 or ≥6.5).
[src:sequential-diverging-palettes/choropleth-map] Because calculated thresholds can often be at precise values that are not easily interpretable by map readers (e.g., $74,326.9734), it is common to create a *modified classification rule* by rounding threshold values to a similar simple number.
[src:sequential-diverging-palettes/choropleth-map] The final element of a choropleth map is the set of colors used to represent the different values of the variable.
[src:sequential-diverging-palettes/choropleth-map] A second general guideline, at least for classified maps, is that the colors should be easily distinguishable, so the colors on the map can be unambiguously matched to those in the legend to determine the represented values.
[src:sequential-diverging-palettes/choropleth-map] This requirement limits the number of classes that can be included; for shades of gray, tests have shown that when value alone is used (e.g., light to dark, whether gray or any single hue), it is difficult to practically use more than seven classes.
[src:sequential-diverging-palettes/choropleth-map] If differences in hue and/or saturation are incorporated, that limit increases significantly to as many as 10-12 classes.
[src:sequential-diverging-palettes/choropleth-map] The need for color discrimination is further impacted by color vision deficiencies; for example, color schemes that use red and green to distinguish values will not be useful for a significant portion of the population.
[src:sequential-diverging-palettes/choropleth-map] It is possible to represent two (and sometimes three) variables simultaneously on a single choropleth map by representing each with a single-hue progression and blending the colors of each district.
[src:sequential-diverging-palettes/choropleth-map] This technique was first published by the U.S.
[src:sequential-diverging-palettes/choropleth-map] Census Bureau in the 1970s, and has been used many times since, to varying degrees of success.
[src:sequential-diverging-palettes/choropleth-map] This technique is generally used to visualize the correlation and contrast between two variables hypothesized to be closely related, such as educational attainment and income.
[src:sequential-diverging-palettes/choropleth-map] Contrasting but not complementary colors are generally used, so that their combination is intuitively recognized as "between" the two original colors, such as red+blue=purple.
[src:sequential-diverging-palettes/choropleth-map] The technique works best when the geography of the variable has a high degree of spatial autocorrelation, so that there are large regions of similar colors with gradual changes between them; otherwise the map can look like a confusing mix of random colors.
[src:sequential-diverging-palettes/choropleth-map] They have been found to be more easily used if the map includes a carefully designed legend and an explanation of the technique.
[src:sequential-diverging-palettes/choropleth-map] A choropleth map uses *ad hoc* symbols to represent the mapped variable.
[src:sequential-diverging-palettes/choropleth-map] While the general strategy may be intuitive if a color progression is chosen that reflects the proper order, map readers cannot decipher the actual value of each district without a legend.
[src:sequential-diverging-palettes/choropleth-map] A typical choropleth legend for a classed choropleth map includes a series of sample patches of the symbol for each class, with a text description of the corresponding range of values.
[src:sequential-diverging-palettes/choropleth-map] On an unclassed choropleth map, it is common for the legend to show a smooth color gradient between the minimum and maximum values, with two or more points along it labeled with corresponding values.
[src:sequential-diverging-palettes/choropleth-map] An alternative approach is the *histogram legend*, which includes a histogram showing the frequency distribution of the mapped variable (i.e., the number of districts in each class).
[src:sequential-diverging-palettes/choropleth-map] Each class may be represented by a single bar with its width determined by its minimum and maximum threshold values and its height calculated such that the box area is proportional to the number of districts included, then colored with the map symbol used for that class.
[src:sequential-diverging-palettes/choropleth-map] Alternatively, the histogram may be divided into a large number of bars, such that each class includes one or more bars, symbolized according to its symbol in the map.
[src:sequential-diverging-palettes/choropleth-map] This form of legend shows not only the threshold values for each class, but gives some context for the source of those values, especially for endogenous classification rules that are based on the frequency distribution, such as quantiles.
[src:sequential-diverging-palettes/choropleth-map] However, they are not currently supported in GIS and mapping software, and must typically be constructed manually.
[src:sequential-diverging-palettes/cielab-color-space] The **CIELAB color space**, also referred to as ***L*a*b****, is a color space defined by the International Commission on Illumination (abbreviated CIE) in 1976.
[src:sequential-diverging-palettes/cielab-color-space] It expresses color as three values: *L** for perceptual lightness and *a** and *b** for the four unique colors of human vision: red, green, blue and yellow.
[src:sequential-diverging-palettes/cielab-color-space] CIELAB was intended as a perceptually uniform space, where a given numerical change corresponds to a similar perceived change in color.
[src:sequential-diverging-palettes/cielab-color-space] While the LAB space is not truly perceptually uniform, it nevertheless is useful in industry for detecting small differences in color.
[src:sequential-diverging-palettes/cielab-color-space] Like the CIEXYZ space it derives from, CIELAB color space is a device-independent, "standard observer" model.
[src:sequential-diverging-palettes/cielab-color-space] The colors it defines are not relative to any particular device such as a computer monitor or a printer, but instead relate to the CIE standard observer which is an averaging of the results of color matching experiments under laboratory conditions.
[src:sequential-diverging-palettes/cielab-color-space] The CIELAB space is three-dimensional and covers the entire gamut (range) of human color perception.
[src:sequential-diverging-palettes/cielab-color-space] It is based on the opponent model of human vision, where red and green form an opponent pair and blue and yellow form an opponent pair.
[src:sequential-diverging-palettes/cielab-color-space] This makes CIELAB a Hering opponent color space.
[src:sequential-diverging-palettes/cielab-color-space] The nature of the transformations also characterizes it as a chromatic value color space.
[src:sequential-diverging-palettes/cielab-color-space] The lightness value, *L** (pronounced "L star"), defines black at 0 and white at 100.
[src:sequential-diverging-palettes/cielab-color-space] The *a** axis is relative to the green–red opponent colors, with negative values toward green and positive values toward red.
[src:sequential-diverging-palettes/cielab-color-space] The *b** axis represents the blue–yellow opponents, with negative numbers toward blue and positive toward yellow.
[src:sequential-diverging-palettes/cielab-color-space] The lightness value, *L** in CIELAB is calculated using the cube root of the relative luminance with an offset near black.
[src:sequential-diverging-palettes/cielab-color-space] This results in an *effective* power curve with an exponent of approximately 0.43 which represents the human eye's response to light under daylight (photopic) conditions.
[src:sequential-diverging-palettes/cielab-color-space] The *a** and *b** axes are unbounded and depending on the reference white they can easily exceed ±150 to cover the human gamut.
[src:sequential-diverging-palettes/cielab-color-space] Nevertheless, software implementations often clamp these values for practical reasons.
[src:sequential-diverging-palettes/cielab-color-space] For instance, if integer math is being used it is common to clamp *a** and *b** in the range of −128 to 127.
[src:sequential-diverging-palettes/cielab-color-space] CIELAB is calculated relative to a reference white, for which the CIE recommends the use of CIE Standard illuminant D65.
[src:sequential-diverging-palettes/cielab-color-space] D65 is used in the vast majority of industries and applications, with the notable exception being the printing industry which uses D50.
[src:sequential-diverging-palettes/cielab-color-space] The International Color Consortium largely supports the printing industry and uses D50 with either CIEXYZ or CIELAB in the Profile Connection Space, for v2 and v4 ICC profiles.
[src:sequential-diverging-palettes/cielab-color-space] While the intention behind CIELAB was to create a space that was more perceptually uniform than CIEXYZ using only a simple formula, CIELAB is known to lack perceptual uniformity, particularly in the area of blue hues.
[src:sequential-diverging-palettes/cielab-color-space] ) plotted within the CIELAB color space.
[src:sequential-diverging-palettes/cielab-color-space] The asterisks (*) after *L**, *a*,* and *b** are pronounced *star* and are part of the full name to distinguish *L***a***b** from Hunter's *Lab*, described below.
[src:sequential-diverging-palettes/cielab-color-space] Since the *L*a*b** model has three axes, it requires a three-dimensional space to be represented completely.
[src:sequential-diverging-palettes/cielab-color-space] Also, because each axis is non-linear, it is not possible to create a two-dimensional chromaticity diagram.
[src:sequential-diverging-palettes/cielab-color-space] Additionally, the visual representations shown in the plots of the full CIELAB gamut on this page are an approximation, as it is impossible for a monitor to display the full gamut of LAB colors.
[src:sequential-diverging-palettes/cielab-color-space] The nonlinear relations for *L**, *a** and *b** are intended to mimic the nonlinear response of the visual system.
[src:sequential-diverging-palettes/cielab-color-space] In order to convert RGB or CMYK values to or from *L*a*b**, the RGB or CMYK data must be linearized relative to light.
[src:sequential-diverging-palettes/cielab-color-space] The reference illuminant of the RGB or CMYK data must be known, as well as the RGB primary coordinates or the CMYK printer's reference data in the form of a color lookup table (CLUT).
[src:sequential-diverging-palettes/cielab-color-space] In color managed systems, ICC profiles contains these needed data, which are then used to perform the conversions.
[src:sequential-diverging-palettes/cielab-color-space] As mentioned previously, the *L** coordinate nominally ranges from 0 to 100.
[src:sequential-diverging-palettes/cielab-color-space] The range of *a** and *b** coordinates is technically unbounded, though it is commonly clamped to the range of −128 to 127 for use with integer code values, though this results in potentially clipping some colors depending on the size of the source color space.
[src:sequential-diverging-palettes/cielab-color-space] The gamut's large size and inefficient utilization of the coordinate space means the best practice is to use floating-point values for all three coordinates.
[src:sequential-diverging-palettes/cielab-color-space] Unlike the RGB and CMYK color models, CIELAB is designed to approximate human vision.
[src:sequential-diverging-palettes/cielab-color-space] The *L** component closely matches human perception of lightness, though it does not take the Helmholtz–Kohlrausch effect into account.
[src:sequential-diverging-palettes/cielab-color-space] CIELAB is less uniform in the color axes, but is useful for predicting small differences in color.
[src:sequential-diverging-palettes/cielab-color-space] The CIELAB coordinate space contains the entire gamut of human color vision, which exceeds the gamut of sRGB or CMYK.
[src:sequential-diverging-palettes/cielab-color-space] In an integer implementation such as TIFF, ICC or Photoshop, the large coordinate space results in substantial data inefficiency due to unused code values.
[src:sequential-diverging-palettes/cielab-color-space] Only about 35% of the available coordinate code values are inside the CIELAB gamut with an integer format.
[src:sequential-diverging-palettes/cielab-color-space] Using CIELAB in an 8-bit per channel integer format typically results in significant quantization errors.
[src:sequential-diverging-palettes/cielab-color-space] Even 16-bit per channel can result in clipping, as the full gamut extends past the bounding coordinate space.
[src:sequential-diverging-palettes/cielab-color-space] Ideally, CIELAB should be used with floating-point data to minimize obvious quantization errors.
[src:sequential-diverging-palettes/cielab-color-space] CIE standards and documents are copyrighted by the CIE and must be purchased; however, the formulas for CIELAB are available on the CIE website.
[src:sequential-diverging-palettes/cielab-color-space] The division of the domain of the f function into two parts was done to prevent an infinite slope at *t* = 0.
[src:sequential-diverging-palettes/cielab-color-space] The function f was assumed to be linear below some *t* = *t*0 and was assumed to match the ${\sqrt[{3}]{t}}$ part of the function at *t*0 in both value and slope.
[src:sequential-diverging-palettes/cielab-color-space] ) plotted within the CIELCHab color space.
[src:sequential-diverging-palettes/cielab-color-space] The "CIELCh" or "CIEHLC" space is a color space based on CIELAB, which uses the polar coordinates *C** (chroma, colorfulness of the color) and *h*° (hue angle, angle of the hue in the CIELAB color wheel) instead of the Cartesian coordinates *a** and *b**.
[src:sequential-diverging-palettes/cielab-color-space] The CIELAB lightness L* remains unchanged.
[src:sequential-diverging-palettes/cielab-color-space] The LCh (or HLC) color space is not the same as the HSV, HSL or HSB color models, although their values can also be interpreted as a base color, saturation and lightness of a color.
[src:sequential-diverging-palettes/cielab-color-space] The HSL values are a polar coordinate transformation of what is technically defined RGB cube color space.
[src:sequential-diverging-palettes/cielab-color-space] Further, *H* and *h* are not identical, because HSL space uses as primary colors the three additive primary colors red, green and blue (*H* = 0, 120, 240°).
[src:sequential-diverging-palettes/cielab-color-space] Instead, the LCh system uses the four colors red, yellow, green and blue (*h* = 0, 90, 180, 270°).
[src:sequential-diverging-palettes/cielab-color-space] Regardless the angle *h*, *C* = 0 means the achromatic colors (non saturated), that is, the gray axis.
[src:sequential-diverging-palettes/cielab-color-space] The simplified spellings LCh, LCh(ab), LCH, LCH(ab) and HLC are common, but the letter presents a different order.
[src:sequential-diverging-palettes/cielab-color-space] HCL color space (Hue-Chroma-Luminance) on the other hand is a commonly used alternative name for the L*C*h(uv) color space, also known as the *cylindrical representation* or *polar CIELUV*.
[src:sequential-diverging-palettes/cielab-color-space] This name is commonly used by information visualization practitioners who want to present data without the bias implicit in using varying saturation.
[src:sequential-diverging-palettes/cielab-color-space] The name Lch(ab) is sometimes used to differentiate from L*C*h(uv).
[src:sequential-diverging-palettes/cielab-color-space] A related color space, the CIE 1976 *L***u***v** color space (a.k.a.
[src:sequential-diverging-palettes/cielab-color-space] CIELUV), preserves the same *L** as *L*a*b** but has a different representation of the chromaticity components.
[src:sequential-diverging-palettes/cielab-color-space] CIELAB and CIELUV can also be expressed in cylindrical form (CIELChab and CIELChuv, respectively), with the chromaticity components replaced by correlates of chroma and hue.
[src:sequential-diverging-palettes/cielab-color-space] Since the work on CIELAB and CIELUV, the CIE has been incorporating an increasing number of color appearance phenomena into their models and difference equations to better predict human color perception.
[src:sequential-diverging-palettes/cielab-color-space] These color appearance models, of which CIELAB is a simple example, culminated with CIECAM02.
[src:sequential-diverging-palettes/cielab-color-space] Oklab is built on the same spatial structure and achieves greater perceptual uniformity.
[src:sequential-diverging-palettes/cielab-color-space] Hunter Lab (also known as Hunter L,a,b) is a color space defined in 1948 by Richard S.
[src:sequential-diverging-palettes/cielab-color-space] It was designed to be computed via simple formulas from the CIEXYZ space, but to be more perceptually uniform.
[src:sequential-diverging-palettes/cielab-color-space] Hunter named his coordinates *L*, *a* and *b*.
[src:sequential-diverging-palettes/cielab-color-space] Hunter Lab was a precursor to CIELAB, created in 1976 by the International Commission on Illumination (CIE), which named the coordinates for CIELAB as *L**, *a**, *b** to distinguish them from Hunter's coordinates.
[src:sequential-diverging-palettes/color-gradient] In color science, a **color gradient** (also known as a **color ramp** or a **color progression**) specifies a range of position-dependent colors, usually used to fill a region.
[src:sequential-diverging-palettes/color-gradient] In assigning colors to a set of values, a gradient is a continuous colormap, a type of color scheme.
[src:sequential-diverging-palettes/color-gradient] In computer graphics, the term swatch has come to mean a palette of active colors.
[src:sequential-diverging-palettes/color-gradient] An axial color gradient (sometimes also called a linear color gradient) is specified by two points, and a color at each point.
[src:sequential-diverging-palettes/color-gradient] The colors along the line through those points are calculated using linear interpolation, then extended perpendicular to that line.
[src:sequential-diverging-palettes/color-gradient] In digital imaging systems, colors are typically interpolated in an RGB color space, often using gamma compressed RGB color values, as opposed to linear.
[src:sequential-diverging-palettes/color-gradient] CSS and SVG both support linear gradients.
[src:sequential-diverging-palettes/color-gradient] A radial gradient is specified as a circle that has one color at the edge and another at the center.
[src:sequential-diverging-palettes/color-gradient] Colors are calculated by linear interpolation based on distance from the center.
[src:sequential-diverging-palettes/color-gradient] This can be used to approximate the diffuse reflection of light from a point source by a sphere.
[src:sequential-diverging-palettes/color-gradient] Both CSS and SVG support radial gradients.
[src:sequential-diverging-palettes/color-gradient] Conic or conical gradients are gradients with color transitions rotated around a center point (rather than radiating from the center).
[src:sequential-diverging-palettes/color-gradient] Example conic gradients include pie charts and color wheels.
[src:sequential-diverging-palettes/color-gradient] Conic gradients are sometimes called "sweep gradients" (for example in the OpenType specification) or angular gradients.
[src:sequential-diverging-palettes/color-gradient] In vector graphics polygon meshes can be used, e.g., Adobe Illustrator supports *gradient meshes*.
[src:sequential-diverging-palettes/color-gradient] The appearance of a gradient not only varies by the color themselves, but also by the color space the calculation is performed in.
[src:sequential-diverging-palettes/color-gradient] A "linear" blend would match physical light blending and has been the standard in game engines for a long time.
[src:sequential-diverging-palettes/color-gradient] On the web, however, it has long been neglected for both color gradients and image scaling.
[src:sequential-diverging-palettes/color-gradient] Such a blend still has a subtle difference from one done in a perceptually-uniform color space.
[src:sequential-diverging-palettes/color-scheme] In color theory, a **color scheme** is a combination of 2 or more colors used in aesthetic or practical design.
[src:sequential-diverging-palettes/color-scheme] Aesthetic color schemes are used to create style and appeal.
[src:sequential-diverging-palettes/color-scheme] Colors that create a harmonious feeling when viewed together are often used together in aesthetic color schemes.
[src:sequential-diverging-palettes/color-scheme] Practical color schemes are used to inhibit or facilitate color tasks, such as camouflage color schemes or high visibility color schemes.
[src:sequential-diverging-palettes/color-scheme] Qualitative and quantitative color schemes are used to encode unordered categorical data and ordered data, respectively.
[src:sequential-diverging-palettes/color-scheme] Color schemes are often described in terms of logical combinations of colors on a color wheel or within a color space.
[src:sequential-diverging-palettes/color-scheme] Harmonious color schemes are designed to accomplish an aesthetic color task and enhance color harmony.
[src:sequential-diverging-palettes/color-scheme] They do not represent any underlying variable.
[src:sequential-diverging-palettes/color-scheme] The color scheme of a logo is typically purely aesthetic.
[src:sequential-diverging-palettes/color-scheme] A color scheme in marketing is referred to as a trade dress and can sometimes be protected by trademark or trade dress laws, as is the pink color of Owens Corning fiberglass.
[src:sequential-diverging-palettes/color-scheme] Any color that lacks strong chromatic content is said to be unsaturated, achromatic, or near neutral.
[src:sequential-diverging-palettes/color-scheme] Pure achromatic colors include black, white, all grays and beiges; near neutrals include browns, tans, pastels, and darker colors.
[src:sequential-diverging-palettes/color-scheme] Near neutrals can be of any hue or lightness.
[src:sequential-diverging-palettes/color-scheme] For example, the "Achromatic" use of a white background with black text is an example of a basic and commonly default color scheme in web design.
[src:sequential-diverging-palettes/color-scheme] Black and white have long been known to combine well with almost any other colors; black decreases the apparent *saturation* or *brightness* of colors paired with it, and white shows off all hues to equal effect.
[src:sequential-diverging-palettes/color-scheme] Monochromatic color schemes may contain all the colors (tints, tones, and shades) of a single hue, i.e. the base hue modified by the addition of black, gray and white.
[src:sequential-diverging-palettes/color-scheme] As a result, the energy is more subtle and peaceful due to a lack of contrast of hue.
[src:sequential-diverging-palettes/color-scheme] A complementary color scheme comprises two colors that combine to form gray, i.e. they are on opposite sides of the color wheel.
[src:sequential-diverging-palettes/color-scheme] Fully saturated complementary colors maximize color contrast.
[src:sequential-diverging-palettes/color-scheme] A *split-complementary* (also called compound harmony) color scheme comprises three colors, namely a base color and two colors that are 150 degrees and 210 degrees apart from the base color.
[src:sequential-diverging-palettes/color-scheme] The split-complementary color scheme has the same sharp visual contrast as the complementary color scheme but has less pressure.
[src:sequential-diverging-palettes/color-scheme] Analogous color schemes (also called dominance harmony) are groups of colors that are adjacent to each other on the color wheel, with one being the dominant color, which tends to be a primary or secondary color, and two on either side complementing, which tend to be tertiary.
[src:sequential-diverging-palettes/color-scheme] This usually translates to a three-color combination consisting of a base color and two colors that are 30 degrees and 330 degrees apart from the base color.
[src:sequential-diverging-palettes/color-scheme] A analogous color scheme tends to have a consistent temperature, comprising only warm or only cool colors.
[src:sequential-diverging-palettes/color-scheme] An analogous color scheme creates a rich, semi-monochromatic look.
[src:sequential-diverging-palettes/color-scheme] However, the scheme also lacks contrast and is less vibrant than complementary schemes.
[src:sequential-diverging-palettes/color-scheme] Red, reddish-orange, orange, yellow-orange is one example of a set of analogous colors.
[src:sequential-diverging-palettes/color-scheme] A *near-analogous* color scheme comprises three colors, namely a base color and two colors that are 60 degrees and 300 degrees apart from the base color.
[src:sequential-diverging-palettes/color-scheme] The near-analogous color scheme has the same consistency as the analogous color scheme but has more contrast in comparison.
[src:sequential-diverging-palettes/color-scheme] One example of a near-analogous color scheme would be red, yellow, and magenta.
[src:sequential-diverging-palettes/color-scheme] An *accented analogous* color scheme adds the complementary color of an analogous color scheme as the accent color, used to create a dominant color grouping of three similar colors accented with the direct complement (or the near complement) of one of them.
[src:sequential-diverging-palettes/color-scheme] The complementary accent color creates an interesting contrast against the dominant color grouping.
[src:sequential-diverging-palettes/color-scheme] This scheme is frequently used to put a warm accent color with a cool analogous color palette, or a cool accent color with a warm palette.
[src:sequential-diverging-palettes/color-scheme] The triadic color scheme is a three-color combination consisting of base color and two colors that are 120 degrees and 240 degrees apart from the base color.
[src:sequential-diverging-palettes/color-scheme] This scheme is popular among artists because it provides sharp visual contrast while maintaining balance and color richness.
[src:sequential-diverging-palettes/color-scheme] The triadic scheme is not as contrasting as the complementary scheme, but it is easier to accomplish balance and harmony with these colors.
[src:sequential-diverging-palettes/color-scheme] The tetradic (also called double complementary) color scheme uses four colors arranged into two complementary color pairs.
[src:sequential-diverging-palettes/color-scheme] This scheme is hard to harmonize and requires a color to dominate or subdue the colors; if all four colors are used in equal amounts, the color scheme may look unbalanced.
[src:sequential-diverging-palettes/color-scheme] The hexadic (also called triple complementary, or double triadic) color scheme is a six-color combination consisting of base color and five colors that are 60, 120, 180, 240 and 300 degrees apart from the base color.
[src:sequential-diverging-palettes/color-scheme] This color scheme uses six colors which are arranged into three complementary color pairs, or it could be seen as two triadic color schemes or two near-analogous color schemes—or adding a complementary pair to a rectangular tetradic color scheme.
[src:sequential-diverging-palettes/color-scheme] An example of this color scheme is red, yellow, green, cyan, blue, and magenta.
[src:sequential-diverging-palettes/color-scheme] Practical color schemes combine colors outside typical aesthetic media and context for purely practical reasons, generally focusing on maximizing or minimizing contrast, instead of color harmony.
[src:sequential-diverging-palettes/color-scheme] The most common practical color scheme is black-and-white, which generally maximizes contrast.
[src:sequential-diverging-palettes/color-scheme] This may be used for black text on a white background or prison uniforms.
[src:sequential-diverging-palettes/color-scheme] Enhancing contrast against a background motivates some practical color schemes, such as high visibility color schemes, while inhibiting contrast against a background motivates others, as in camouflage.
[src:sequential-diverging-palettes/color-scheme] Qualitative color schemes represent categorical variables, where the possible values of the variable are discrete and unordered.
[src:sequential-diverging-palettes/color-scheme] An example of a categorical variable is U.S. states, which has 50 unordered values.
[src:sequential-diverging-palettes/color-scheme] A qualitative color scheme is generally also called a color code.
[src:sequential-diverging-palettes/color-scheme] Generally, the number of colors in a qualitative color scheme is equal to the number of possible values for the categorical variable, where each value is encoded to one color.
[src:sequential-diverging-palettes/color-scheme] However, the number of total colors can be decreased by encoding each value with multiple colors, as in the 25-pair color code, which encodes 25 values using only 10 colors, by assigning each value a color each from group A and group B, each consisting of 5 colors.
[src:sequential-diverging-palettes/color-scheme] A qualitative color scheme can be designed similarly to a harmonious color scheme.
[src:sequential-diverging-palettes/color-scheme] However, the goal of a qualitative color scheme is to solve a comparative color task rather than an aesthetic color task, so enhancing color difference between the colors in the color scheme is generally more important than color harmony.
[src:sequential-diverging-palettes/color-scheme] Quantitative schemes are fundamental to Thematic maps, charts, data science, spreadsheets, and other tools which use graphical means to visualize quantitative data.
[src:sequential-diverging-palettes/color-scheme] They are common in heat maps, choropleths and other forms of visualization.
[src:sequential-diverging-palettes/color-scheme] These color schemes can be categorized into different classes, depending on the nature of the underlying data.
[src:sequential-diverging-palettes/color-scheme] Scientifically derived color schemes (or scientific color maps) seek to improve on traditional color schemes (spectral schemes such as *rainbow* or *jet*) by incorporating a uniform color gradient and color blind accessibility.
[src:sequential-diverging-palettes/color-scheme] In the 1990s, Cynthia Brewer performed a number of experiments on various color schemes for data visualization in maps, especially working with those with color blindness.
[src:sequential-diverging-palettes/color-scheme] Eventually, this work led to a palette of several dozen color schemes designed to be reproducible on multiple devices and usable by the color blind, which was collected into an interactive tool known as ColorBrewer in 2002.
[src:sequential-diverging-palettes/color-scheme] This palette quickly gained wide acceptance due to its reliable usability by non-experts, and has become a standard built into GIS and mapping software and other visualization tools.
[src:sequential-diverging-palettes/color-scheme] Connotative color schemes use colors that reference a specific cultural meaning.
[src:sequential-diverging-palettes/color-scheme] Red and green color schemes are connotative of Christmas.
[src:sequential-diverging-palettes/color-scheme] In some countries, a red, white and blue color scheme connotes the Flag of the United States.
[src:sequential-diverging-palettes/color-scheme] In hotel room designs, the relationship between preferences of color schemes and gender was detected.
[src:sequential-diverging-palettes/color-scheme] Male guests tend to prefer masculine color schemes, while female guests favor feminine color schemes.
[src:sequential-diverging-palettes/color-space] A **color space** is a specific organization of colors.
[src:sequential-diverging-palettes/color-space] In combination with color profiling supported by various physical devices, it supports reproducible representations of color – whether such representation entails an analog or a digital representation.
[src:sequential-diverging-palettes/color-space] A "color space" is a useful conceptual tool for understanding the color capabilities of a particular device or digital file.
[src:sequential-diverging-palettes/color-space] When trying to reproduce color on another device, color spaces can show whether shadow/highlight detail and color saturation can be retained, and by how much either will be compromised.
[src:sequential-diverging-palettes/color-space] Adding a specific mapping function between a color model and a reference color space establishes within the reference color space a definite "footprint", known as a *gamut*, and for a given color model, this defines a color space.
[src:sequential-diverging-palettes/color-space] For example, Adobe RGB and sRGB are two different absolute color spaces, both based on the RGB color model.
[src:sequential-diverging-palettes/color-space] When defining a color space, the usual reference standard is the CIELAB or CIEXYZ color spaces, which were specifically designed to encompass all colors the average human can see.
[src:sequential-diverging-palettes/color-space] Since "color space" identifies a particular combination of the color model and the mapping function, the word is often used informally to identify a color model.
[src:sequential-diverging-palettes/color-space] However, even though identifying a color space automatically identifies the associated color model, this usage is incorrect in a strict sense.
[src:sequential-diverging-palettes/color-space] For example, although several specific color spaces are based on the RGB color model, there is no such thing as the singular RGB color space.
[src:sequential-diverging-palettes/color-space] In 1802, Thomas Young postulated the existence of three types of photoreceptors (now known as cone cells) in the eye, each of which was sensitive to a particular range of visible light.
[src:sequential-diverging-palettes/color-space] Hermann von Helmholtz developed the Young–Helmholtz theory further in 1850: that the three types of cone photoreceptors could be classified as short-preferring (blue), middle-preferring (green), and long-preferring (red), according to their response to the wavelengths of light striking the retina.
[src:sequential-diverging-palettes/color-space] The relative strengths of the signals detected by the three types of cones are interpreted by the brain as a visible color.
[src:sequential-diverging-palettes/color-space] But it is not clear that they thought of colors as being points in color space.
[src:sequential-diverging-palettes/color-space] The color-space concept was likely due to Hermann Grassmann, who developed it in two stages.
[src:sequential-diverging-palettes/color-space] First, he developed the idea of vector space, which allowed the algebraic representation of geometric concepts in *n*-dimensional space.
[src:sequential-diverging-palettes/color-space] With this conceptual background, in 1853, Grassmann published a theory of how colors mix; it and its three color laws are still taught, as Grassmann's law.
[src:sequential-diverging-palettes/color-space] Colors can be created in printing with color spaces based on the CMYK color model, using the subtractive primary colors of pigment (**c**yan, **m**agenta, **y**ellow, and **k**ey [black]).
[src:sequential-diverging-palettes/color-space] To create a three-dimensional representation of a given color space, we can assign the amount of magenta color to the representation's X axis, the amount of cyan to its Y axis, and the amount of yellow to its Z axis.
[src:sequential-diverging-palettes/color-space] The resulting 3-D space provides a unique position for every possible color that can be created by combining those three pigments.
[src:sequential-diverging-palettes/color-space] Colors can be created on computer monitors with color spaces based on the RGB color model, using the additive primary colors (red, green, and blue).
[src:sequential-diverging-palettes/color-space] A three-dimensional representation would assign each of the three colors to the X, Y, and Z axes.
[src:sequential-diverging-palettes/color-space] Colors generated on a given monitor will be limited by the reproduction medium, such as the phosphor (in a CRT monitor) or filters and backlight (LCD monitor).
[src:sequential-diverging-palettes/color-space] Another way of creating colors on a monitor is with an HSL or HSV color model, based on hue, saturation, brightness (value/lightness).
[src:sequential-diverging-palettes/color-space] With such a model, the variables are assigned to cylindrical coordinates.
[src:sequential-diverging-palettes/color-space] Many color spaces can be represented as three-dimensional values in this manner, but some have more, or fewer dimensions, and some, such as Pantone, cannot be represented in this way at all.
[src:sequential-diverging-palettes/color-space] Color space conversion is the translation of the representation of a color from one basis to another.
[src:sequential-diverging-palettes/color-space] This typically occurs in the context of converting an image that is represented in one color space to another color space, the goal being to make the translated image look as similar as possible to the original.
[src:sequential-diverging-palettes/color-space] The RGB color model is implemented in different ways, depending on the capabilities of the system used.
[src:sequential-diverging-palettes/color-space] The most common incarnation in general use as of 2021 is the 24-bit implementation, with 8 bits, or 256 discrete levels of color per channel.
[src:sequential-diverging-palettes/color-space] Any color space based on such a 24-bit RGB model is thus limited to a range of 256×256×256 ≈ 16.7 million colors.
[src:sequential-diverging-palettes/color-space] Some implementations use 16 bits per component for 48 bits total, resulting in the same gamut with a larger number of distinct colors.
[src:sequential-diverging-palettes/color-space] This is especially important when working with wide-gamut color spaces (where most of the more common colors are located relatively close together), or when a large number of digital filtering algorithms are used consecutively.
[src:sequential-diverging-palettes/color-space] The same principle applies for any color space based on the same color model, but implemented at different bit depths.
[src:sequential-diverging-palettes/color-space] CIE 1931 XYZ color space was one of the first attempts to produce a color space based on measurements of human color perception (earlier efforts were by James Clerk Maxwell, König & Dieterici, and Abney at Imperial College) and it is the basis for almost all other color spaces.
[src:sequential-diverging-palettes/color-space] The CIERGB color space is a linearly-related companion of CIE XYZ.
[src:sequential-diverging-palettes/color-space] Additional derivatives of CIE XYZ include the CIELUV, CIEUVW, and CIELAB.
[src:sequential-diverging-palettes/color-space] RGB uses additive color mixing, because it describes what kind of *light* needs to be *emitted* to produce a given color.
[src:sequential-diverging-palettes/color-space] RGB stores individual values for red, green and blue.
[src:sequential-diverging-palettes/color-space] RGBA is RGB with an additional channel, alpha, to indicate transparency.
[src:sequential-diverging-palettes/color-space] Common color spaces based on the RGB model include sRGB, Adobe RGB, ProPhoto RGB, scRGB, and CIE RGB.
[src:sequential-diverging-palettes/color-space] CMYK uses subtractive color mixing used in the printing process, because it describes what kind of inks need to be applied so the light *reflected* from the substrate and through the inks produces a given color.
[src:sequential-diverging-palettes/color-space] One starts with a white substrate (canvas, page, etc.), and uses ink to subtract color from white to create an image.
[src:sequential-diverging-palettes/color-space] CMYK stores ink values for cyan, magenta, yellow and black.
[src:sequential-diverging-palettes/color-space] There are many CMYK color spaces for different sets of inks, substrates, and press characteristics (which change the dot gain or transfer function for each ink and thus change the appearance).
[src:sequential-diverging-palettes/color-space] YIQ was formerly used in NTSC (North America, Japan and elsewhere) television broadcasts for historical reasons.
[src:sequential-diverging-palettes/color-space] This system stores a luma value roughly analogous to (and sometimes incorrectly identified as) luminance, along with two chroma values as approximate representations of the relative amounts of blue and red in the color.
[src:sequential-diverging-palettes/color-space] It is similar to the YUV scheme used in most video capture systems and in PAL (Australia, Europe, except France, which uses SECAM) television, except that the YIQ color space is rotated 33° with respect to the YUV color space and the color axes are swapped.
[src:sequential-diverging-palettes/color-space] The YDbDr scheme used by SECAM television is rotated in another way.
[src:sequential-diverging-palettes/color-space] It is most commonly seen in its digital form, YCbCr, used widely in video and image compression schemes such as MPEG and JPEG.
[src:sequential-diverging-palettes/color-space] xvYCC is an international digital video color space standard published by the IEC (IEC 61966-2-4).
[src:sequential-diverging-palettes/color-space] It is based on the ITU BT.601 and BT.709 standards but extends the gamut beyond the R/G/B primaries specified in those standards.
[src:sequential-diverging-palettes/color-space] HSV (**h**ue, **s**aturation, **v**alue), also known as HSB (hue, saturation, **b**rightness) is often used by artists because it is often more natural to think about a color in terms of hue and saturation than in terms of additive or subtractive color components.
[src:sequential-diverging-palettes/color-space] HSV is a transformation of an RGB color space, and its components and colorimetry are relative to the RGB color space from which it was derived.
[src:sequential-diverging-palettes/color-space] HSL (**h**ue, **s**aturation, **l**ightness/**l**uminance), also known as HLS or HSI (hue, saturation, **i**ntensity) is quite similar to HSV, with "lightness" replacing "brightness".
[src:sequential-diverging-palettes/color-space] The difference is that the *brightness* of a pure color is equal to the brightness of white, while the *lightness* of a pure color is equal to the lightness of a medium gray.
[src:sequential-diverging-palettes/color-space] They largely ignored blue light because the added complexity of a 3-component process provided only a marginal increase in fidelity when compared to the jump from monochrome to 2-component color.
[src:sequential-diverging-palettes/color-space] In this article, we concentrate on the second definition.
[src:sequential-diverging-palettes/color-space] CIEXYZ, sRGB, and ICtCp are examples of absolute color spaces, as opposed to a generic RGB color space.
[src:sequential-diverging-palettes/color-space] A non-absolute color space can be made absolute by defining its relationship to absolute colorimetric quantities.
[src:sequential-diverging-palettes/color-space] For instance, if the red, green, and blue colors in a monitor are measured exactly, together with other properties of the monitor, then RGB values on that monitor can be considered as absolute.
[src:sequential-diverging-palettes/color-space] The CIE 1976 L*, a*, b* color space is sometimes referred to as absolute, though it also needs a white point specification to make it so.
[src:sequential-diverging-palettes/color-space] A popular way to make a color space like RGB into an absolute color is to define an ICC profile, which contains the attributes of the RGB.
[src:sequential-diverging-palettes/color-space] This is not the only way to express an absolute color, but it is the standard in many industries.
[src:sequential-diverging-palettes/color-space] RGB colors defined by widely accepted profiles include sRGB and Adobe RGB.
[src:sequential-diverging-palettes/color-space] The process of adding an ICC profile to a graphic or document is sometimes called *tagging* or *embedding*; tagging, therefore, marks the absolute meaning of colors in that graphic or document.
[src:sequential-diverging-palettes/color-space] A color in one absolute color space can be converted into another absolute color space, and back again, in general; however, some color spaces may have gamut limitations, and converting colors that lie outside that gamut will not produce correct results.
[src:sequential-diverging-palettes/color-space] There are also likely to be rounding errors, especially if the popular range of only 256 distinct values per component (8-bit color) is used.
[src:sequential-diverging-palettes/color-space] One part of the definition of an absolute color space is the viewing conditions.
[src:sequential-diverging-palettes/color-space] The same color, viewed under different natural or artificial lighting conditions, will look different.
[src:sequential-diverging-palettes/color-space] Those involved professionally with color matching may use viewing rooms, lit by standardized lighting.
[src:sequential-diverging-palettes/color-space] Occasionally, there are precise rules for converting between non-absolute color spaces.
[src:sequential-diverging-palettes/color-space] For example, HSL and HSV spaces are defined as mappings of RGB.
[src:sequential-diverging-palettes/color-space] Both are non-absolute, but the conversion between them should maintain the same color.
[src:sequential-diverging-palettes/color-space] However, in general, converting between two non-absolute color spaces (for example, RGB to CMYK) or between absolute and non-absolute color spaces (for example, RGB to L*a*b*) is almost a meaningless concept.
[src:sequential-diverging-palettes/color-space] A different method of defining absolute color spaces is familiar to many consumers as the swatch card, used to select paint, fabrics, and the like.
[src:sequential-diverging-palettes/color-space] This is a way of agreeing a color between two parties.
[src:sequential-diverging-palettes/color-space] A more standardized method of defining absolute colors is the Pantone Matching System, a proprietary system that includes swatch cards and recipes that commercial printers can use to make inks that are a particular color.
[src:sequential-diverging-palettes/false-color] The concept behind **true color** can help in understanding false color.
[src:sequential-diverging-palettes/false-color] An image is called a *true-color* image when it offers a natural color rendition, or when it comes close to it.
[src:sequential-diverging-palettes/false-color] This means that the colors of an object in an image appear to a human observer the same way as if this same observer were to directly view the object: A green tree appears green in the image, a red apple red, a blue sky blue, and so on.
[src:sequential-diverging-palettes/false-color] This true-color image shows the area in actual colors, e.g., the vegetation appears in green.
[src:sequential-diverging-palettes/false-color] , red and green spectral bands mapped to RGB – this image shows vegetation in a red tone, as vegetation reflects most light in the near infrared.
[src:sequential-diverging-palettes/false-color] Absolute true-color rendering is impossible.
[src:sequential-diverging-palettes/false-color] The result of a metameric failure would be for example an image of a green tree which shows a different shade of green than the tree itself, a different shade of red for a red apple, a different shade of blue for the blue sky, and so on.
[src:sequential-diverging-palettes/false-color] Color management (e.g. with ICC profiles) can be used to mitigate this problem within the physical constraints.
[src:sequential-diverging-palettes/false-color] spectral bands (blue / green, green and near infrared).
[src:sequential-diverging-palettes/false-color] In contrast to a true-color image, a **false-color image** sacrifices natural color rendition in order to ease the detection of features that are not readily discernible otherwise – for example the use of near infrared for the detection of vegetation in satellite images.
[src:sequential-diverging-palettes/false-color] While a false-color image can be created using solely the visual spectrum (e.g. to accentuate color differences), typically some or all data used is from electromagnetic radiation (EM) outside the visual spectrum (e.g. infrared, ultraviolet or X-ray).
[src:sequential-diverging-palettes/false-color] The choice of spectral bands is governed by the physical properties of the object under investigation.
[src:sequential-diverging-palettes/false-color] As the human eye uses three spectral bands (see trichromacy for details), three spectral bands are commonly combined into a false-color image.
[src:sequential-diverging-palettes/false-color] At least two spectral bands are needed for a false-color encoding, and it is possible to combine more bands into the three visual RGB bands – with the eye's ability to discern three channels being the limiting factor.
[src:sequential-diverging-palettes/false-color] In contrast, a "color" image made from one spectral band, or an image made from data consisting of non-EM data (e.g. elevation, temperature, tissue type) is a *pseudocolor image* (see below).
[src:sequential-diverging-palettes/false-color] For true color, the RGB channels (red "R", green "G" and blue "B") from the camera are mapped to the corresponding RGB channels of the image, yielding a "RGB→RGB" mapping.
[src:sequential-diverging-palettes/false-color] For false color this relationship is changed.
[src:sequential-diverging-palettes/false-color] The simplest false-color encoding is to take an RGB image in the visible spectrum, but map it differently, e.g.
[src:sequential-diverging-palettes/false-color] For traditional false-color satellite images of Earth a "NRG→RGB" mapping is used, with "N" being the near-infrared spectral band (and the blue spectral band being unused) – this yields the typical "vegetation in red" false-color images.
[src:sequential-diverging-palettes/false-color] False color is used (among others) for satellite and space images: Examples are remote sensing satellites (e.g.
[src:sequential-diverging-palettes/false-color] Landsat, see example above), space telescopes (e.g. the Hubble Space Telescope) or space probes (e.g.
[src:sequential-diverging-palettes/false-color] Some spacecraft, with rovers (e.g. the Mars Science Laboratory *Curiosity*) being the most prominent examples, have the ability to capture approximate true-color images as well.
[src:sequential-diverging-palettes/false-color] Weather satellites produce, in contrast to the spacecraft mentioned previously, grayscale images from the visible or infrared spectrum.
[src:sequential-diverging-palettes/false-color] : The left image shows vegetation density and the middle image presence of water (greens / blue for wet soil and red for dry soil).
[src:sequential-diverging-palettes/false-color] , as is particularly the case in fields 120 and 119 (indicated by red and yellow pixels).
[src:sequential-diverging-palettes/false-color] These fields were due to be irrigated the following day.
[src:sequential-diverging-palettes/false-color] is false-color, as can be inferred from the pink stars.
[src:sequential-diverging-palettes/false-color] , the first picking up light in the frequency of sulfur ions (arbitrarily assigned to the color red), the second hydrogen (green), and the third oxygen ions (blue).
[src:sequential-diverging-palettes/false-color] The actual color of the nebula is unknown, but if viewed at a distance making the 1-light-year-long "pillars" similarly visible, it would probably appear as a nearly uniform brownish grey to human eyes.
[src:sequential-diverging-palettes/false-color] False color has a range of scientific applications.
[src:sequential-diverging-palettes/false-color] Spacecraft often employ false-color methods to help understand the composition of structures in the universe such as nebula and galaxies.
[src:sequential-diverging-palettes/false-color] The frequency of light emitted by different ions in space are assigned contrasting colors, allowing the chemical composition of complex structures to be better separated and visualised.
[src:sequential-diverging-palettes/false-color] The image of the Eagle Nebula above is a typical example of this; the Hydrogen and Oxygen ions have been assigned green and blue respectively.
[src:sequential-diverging-palettes/false-color] The large amounts of green and blue in the image show that there is a large amount of Hydrogen and Oxygen in the nebula.
[src:sequential-diverging-palettes/false-color] On 26 October 2004, the NASA/ESA Cassini-Huygens spacecraft captured a false-color image of Titan, Saturn's largest moon.
[src:sequential-diverging-palettes/false-color] The image was captured in Ultraviolet and Infrared wavelengths, both invisible to the human eye.
[src:sequential-diverging-palettes/false-color] In order to provide a visual representation, false color techniques were used.
[src:sequential-diverging-palettes/false-color] The infrared data was mapped to red and green colors, and ultraviolet mapped to blue.
[src:sequential-diverging-palettes/false-color] A **pseudocolor** image (sometimes styled **pseudo-color** or **pseudo color**) is derived from a grayscale image by mapping each intensity value to a color according to a table or function.
[src:sequential-diverging-palettes/false-color] Pseudo color is typically used when a single channel of data is available (e.g. temperature, elevation, soil composition, tissue type, and so on), in contrast to false color which is commonly used to display three channels of data.
[src:sequential-diverging-palettes/false-color] Pseudocoloring can make some details more visible, as the perceived difference in color space is bigger than between successive gray levels alone.
[src:sequential-diverging-palettes/false-color] On the other hand, the color mapping function should be chosen to make sure the lightness of the color is still monotonic, or the uneven change would make it hard to interpret levels, for both normal and colorblind viewers.
[src:sequential-diverging-palettes/false-color] One offender is the commonly used "rainbow" palette, with a back-and-forth change in lightness.
[src:sequential-diverging-palettes/false-color] A typical example for the use of pseudo color is thermography (thermal imaging), where infrared cameras feature only one spectral band and show their grayscale images in pseudo color.
[src:sequential-diverging-palettes/false-color] in the foreground and a traditional building in the background.
[src:sequential-diverging-palettes/false-color] There is a color to temperature key on the right.
[src:sequential-diverging-palettes/false-color] using pseudocolor encoding – yellow/white indicates hot and red/violet indicates cool.
[src:sequential-diverging-palettes/false-color] Areas reaching 3,000 °F (1,650 °C) can be seen in yellow.
[src:sequential-diverging-palettes/false-color] Another familiar example of pseudo color is the encoding of elevation using hypsometric tints in physical relief maps, where negative values (below sea level) are usually represented by shades of blue, and positive values by greens and browns.
[src:sequential-diverging-palettes/false-color] , showing ocean floor in shades of blue and land in greens and browns.
[src:sequential-diverging-palettes/false-color] There is a color to elevation key on the bottom.
[src:sequential-diverging-palettes/false-color] with hypsometric tints of red for the highest points and purple for the lowest.
[src:sequential-diverging-palettes/false-color] Depending on the table or function used and the choice of data sources, pseudocoloring may increase the information contents of the original image, for example adding geographic information, combining information obtained from infrared or ultra-violet light, or other sources like MRI scans.
[src:sequential-diverging-palettes/false-color] This image shows compositional variations of the Moon overlaid as pseudo color.
[src:sequential-diverging-palettes/false-color] A grayscale MRI of a knee – different gray levels indicate different tissue types, requiring a trained eye.
[src:sequential-diverging-palettes/false-color] A pseudocolor MRI of a knee created using three different grayscale scans – tissue types are easier to discern through pseudo color.
[src:sequential-diverging-palettes/false-color] A further application of pseudocoloring is to store the results of image elaboration; that is, changing the colors in order to ease understanding an image.
[src:sequential-diverging-palettes/false-color] A **choropleth** is an image or map in which areas are colored or patterned proportionally to the category or value of one or more variables being represented.
[src:sequential-diverging-palettes/false-color] The variables are mapped to a few colors; each area contributes one data point and receives one color from these selected colors.
[src:sequential-diverging-palettes/false-color] Basically, it is density slicing applied to a pseudocolor overlay.
[src:sequential-diverging-palettes/false-color] A choropleth map of a geographic area is thus an extreme form of false color.
[src:sequential-diverging-palettes/false-color] While artistic rendition lends to subjective expression of color, Andy Warhol (1928–1987) has become a culturally significant figure of the modern art movement by creating false-color paintings with screen printing techniques.
[src:sequential-diverging-palettes/false-color] Some of Warhol's most recognizable prints include a replication of Marilyn Monroe, her image based on a film frame from the movie *Niagara*.
[src:sequential-diverging-palettes/false-color] The subject was a sex symbol and film noir starlet whose death in 1962 influenced the artist.
[src:sequential-diverging-palettes/false-color] A series of prints were made with endearment but expose her persona as an illusion through his assembly line style of art production which are non-erotic and slightly grotesque.
[src:sequential-diverging-palettes/false-color] Using various ink color palettes, Warhol immersed himself in a process of repetition that serves to compare personas and everyday objects to the qualities of mass production and consumerism.
[src:sequential-diverging-palettes/false-color] The colors of ink were selected through experimentation of aesthetics and do not correlate to false-color rendering of the electromagnetic spectrum employed in remote sensing image processing.
[src:sequential-diverging-palettes/false-color] For years the artist continued screen printing false-color images of Marilyn Monroe, perhaps his most referenced work being *Turquoise Marilyn* which was bought in May 2007 by a private collector for 80 million US dollars.
